      {
        "content": "block.timestamp used as randomness / deadline allows miner influence\n\nA lottery selects winners using block.timestamp % n and a vesting cliff compares against block.timestamp. Validators can nudge timestamps within ~15s, biasing outcomes near boundaries. Fix: do not use block.timestamp for randomness (use a VRF); for deadlines, accept the small manipulation window only where economically irrelevant.",
        "doc_id": "code4rena-timestamp-deadline-bypass",
        "chunk_id": 0,
        "total_chunks": 1,
        "metadata": {
          "protocol": "Lottery",
          "date": "2023-08-09",
          "vuln_type": "timestamp",
          "severity": "medium",
          "loss_usd": 0,
          "chain": "ethereum",
          "url": "https://code4rena.com/reports",
          "source": "code4rena",
          "chunk_id": 0,
          "total_chunks": 1,
          "doc_id": "code4rena-timestamp-deadline-bypass"
        },
        "score": 0.03306010928961749
      },
      {
        "content": "SWC-116: Block values as a proxy for time\n\nContracts often use block.timestamp / block.number for time-dependent logic. Miners/validators can manipulate block.timestamp within a small window, and block times vary. Remediation: avoid block values for randomness; tolerate the manipulation window for deadlines only where economically safe.",
        "doc_id": "SWC-116",
        "chunk_id": 0,
        "total_chunks": 1,
        "metadata": {
